Complete Lesson

The 5 Phases of Craftship: The Straight-Line Path to Rapid Improvement as a Developer

Introduction/hook

Forget junior or senior.

That doesn't mean anything anymore.

I've met all-star prodigy junior developers who are just kicking back with fat paychecks, sipping lattes, ski-trips, and building dope Serverless AI-side projects in their free time.

Not a bad life at all, man.

On the flip side, I’ve met senior developers still copying and pasting code from Stack Overflow trying to figure out how to center a div.

Been there.

Look. We’ve talked a lot already about staying attuned to reality.

The reality is this: your title ≠ your skill level.

So instead of focusing on your title, focus instead on Value and your ability as a software developer to realize it.

As you get better with the 12 essentials, you’ll spend less time thinking about code and more time thinking about the value behind what you’re doing.

Eventually, something weird happens.

You go from asking questions like this:

  • how can I make this code work?
  • what are the best practices here?
  • what’s the ddd-way to solve this problem?

To asking questions like this…

  • am I aligned to the work I’m doing here?
  • what kinds of companies do I want to work at?
  • what would fulfill me most in my career?
  • how would I like to use my skills to create a meaningful impact in my life? for my family? for my community?

Value-creating software developers live lives of creative, authentic freedom and abundance to do and work on what they’d like.

As Brian Tracy says:

“You become what you think about most of the time.”

So we need to go from Code-First to Value-First.

Let’s discuss how we’re going to embark on this journey.

Lesson goals

In this lesson, we’re going to briefly cover:

  • What the Phases of Craftship are
  • How each of the 5 Phases differs in how you see code, where folks get stuck, and what we’ll focus on in order to keep moving forward
  • The homework structure and resources we’ll employ in the upcoming modules: assignments, exercises, demonstrations, feedback & assessments

Where are we so far?

Before we get into it, let’s quickly recap.

The main purpose of this course is to develop your problem decomposition skills and turn you into a confident software developer.

Right? Right.

And what did we learn in the metaphysics?

We’ve learned that the 4 pillars of scalable software development — that is, your design, testing, architecture & strategy — well, these are the things that will have the greatest impact on your ability to write scalable code and make good decisions.

However, we also learned that it’s really hard to learn the 4 pillars directly.

A Maze of Topics: We covered this in Abstraction, but just look at this crazy maze of topics you’ll need to know to implement E2E Testing from UI to DB properly (you’ll be doing this in BP-First btw).

There’s just… so much to learn… and it’s all interconnected and intertwined.

Decomposing the complexity of mastering what matters: Because of this, we’ve learned that it is much more practical to merely learn the 12 essentials — way, smaller slices of the 4-pillar-pie — and practice applying these gradually.

And this is exactly where the Phases of Craftship come in.

What are the Phases of Craftship?

The 5 Phases of Craftship mark different mental operating systems or skill/knowledge/problem-decomposition levels you have as a software developer.

Going from Code-First to Value-First, the Phases of Craftship is also basically the invisible apprenticeship program I’ve identified in myself and other developers who’ve embarked on the path of attempting to master what matters.

What changes as you move up the Phases?

The way you use Abstraction changes

Abstraction is the essential of problem decomposition.

Moving through the Phases involves changing your abstraction paradigm a few times.

When you first start out as a developer, the way you solve problems — the way you think about & write code — is immature. That’s normal.

As a Code-First developer, you see code, the various tools, libraries, and frameworks you use to solve problems as if they’re big building blocks you can plug together to make “an app”.

Frontend + backend +database = app.

Compare this to the Responsibility-First developer — to them, a block of code is nothing more than a set of responsibilities organized into stereotypical roles which collaborate with each other.

Sorry, what? Roles, responsibilities & collaborations? The quick gist is this: the lowest level of looking at code, the lowest level of abstraction? It’s responsibilities. Every single line of code you write represents something that is either done or something that is known. Those responsibilities get organized into roles which live in layers and collaborate with other roles. Yeah, I know. Head spinning. We’ll get to this in Responsibility-First, but consider this the first poke at it to know where we’re going. By the way, this is actually one of my favourite topics in all of software design, so if you’re eager to know more right now, I’d recommend you 1) Check out this article on Object Stereotypes, 2) have a read of “3 Steps to Solve Most Design Problems” and see how much you understand, and 3) get your free copy of the legendary Object Design book. Won’t be all that useful to you as a Code or Best-Practice first developer, but when you’re Pattern-First, it’s seriously life changing.

Your priorities shift (from using code to solving problems in the most valuable way)

When you’re at the code-first phase you prioritize just making things work.

Pattern-first developers prioritize testing strategies and building a shared understanding of the problem.

Value-first developers prioritize doing whatever matters the most — which can vary widely depending on the context. It might mean writing a spreadsheet instead of writing code. It might mean fleshing out an insanely awesome test suite.

You can apply the 12 essentials with more depth

Remember playing Fallout or Skyrim where you got to load up your character’s stats?

Well, when you start off as a Code-First developer, your stats are pretty low for most of the essentials.

As a code-first frontend developer, the way you perform Subject Verification — which, if you remember from The Metaphysics, is how you verify what you’ve coded works.

Quite often, the way we do this is to merely save your code and reload the page.

Works, but… not the best, right?

Compared to the Pattern-First developer’s approach of utilizing various forms of High Value Unit, Integration, Contract and E2E Tests as a testing strategy to ensure their code stays valuable and intact as they make changes over time?

Blown outta the water.

(Also: Not to mention Pattern-First developers tend to use these tests in their CI/CD pipeline to ensure they don’t ship bugs to users).

The 5 Phases

With all that said, at a high level, here’s what each of these phases are, what some of the challenges you’re likely to encounter are, and what we’ll do to move forward in the course.

Coming next: Following these lessons is an assessment you can use to determine which Phase you’re likely at right now.

We’ll go deeper on this when we need to: I’m intentionally keeping it high level here. We’ll discuss the context, problems, strengths, and techniques prioritized for each phase, at the start of a new phase.

Code-First

Paradigm: At the Code-First Phase, the focus is on making things work; you see code, tools, libraries, frameworks and languages as the building blocks to piece it all together.

Context: Typically, if you’re employed, it’s as a frontend developer who works on building screens and light functionality. This is easy for you. You might not have a deep understanding of the tools you're using, but that's OK. This is what got you into the industry. You want to challenge yourself by venturing into backend, building your own products, and taking on more fulfilling, higher-paid work.

Drawbacks: The main vulnerability of the code-first phase is the sheer amount of unknown unknowns, keeping out of tutorial hell and knowing what one should focus on next to continue to improve.

⚡️ To Mastery! The 4 Pillars: At this phase, you can use the basics of your tools to make things work BUT struggle with strategy, testing, and design/arch confidence.

What we’ll do to improve in the course: We’ll shift our focus to becoming full-stack, taking on challenges that adopt more responsibility by building a system end to end (frontend to backend)

Key topics: MVC

Best Practice-First

Paradigm: The key shift from Code-First to Best Practice-First is the prioritization of quality through best practices.

Context: You’ve gotten pretty good at using your tools and kept up to date on the best practices as per the developer tooling companies, docs & their developer advocates. While you can use their patterns and approaches, you’re still noticing that your code tends to turn into a spaghetti mess for some reason. You’ve decided to start studying topics such as SOLID, the 4 principles of object-oriented programming, clean architecture, clean code and and so on. However, there’s still a strong feeling of “I’m not sure how to implement this properly” and "I'm not sure this is actually going to help".

Drawbacks: Best Practice-seeking developers tend to get stuck in the dogma-zone; that is, following common advice without fully understanding the first principles of why such practices are good or bad. This makes for faulty decision-making.

⚡️ To Mastery! The 4 Pillars: At this phase, you can utilize the best practices and patterns of frameworks & libraries to coarsely solve problems using tools such as React, Redux, Nest.js, Next.js, these are not best practices and patterns based on the first principles. You can make things work BUT struggle with strategy, testing, design/arch confidence.

What we’ll do to improve in the course: We’ll focus on learning how to kick off a project from solid fundamentals using the best of TDD, BDD & Continuous Delivery to design, build, test & deploy a Walking Skeleton.

Key topics: Test-Driven Development, Behaviour-Driven Development, Continuous Delivery

Pattern-First

Paradigm: The key shift from Best Practice-First to Pattern-First is a focus on understanding the domain, the ubiquitous language, and the patterns used to organize your code and test with a higher level of flexibility & dexterity.

Domain-Driven Design & the Ubiquitous (common) language: Ah yes, Domain-Driven Design. We discussed this in the Domain Discovery essential, but in as little words as possible, Domain-Driven Design involves 1) a focus on understanding the problem using the exact same language that the domain experts (users & customers — stakeholders) use, 2) creating a shared understanding of the problem (ie: the domain model), 3) taking that shared understanding, and then embedding it into your codebase as a domain model implementation — which is a layer of code based entirely on this common language! It leads to a lot more maintainable code. Incredibly powerful stuff.

Context: At some point, you realize you need to get a closer understanding of the nature of the problem to be solved. Eventually you learn that you should focus on the domain instead. This introduces you to wonderful world of Domain-Driven Design. The most common benefit developers take away from this phase is how to organize their code into patterns, how to discover the Ubiquitous/Common Language, and important architectural concepts like CQRS & the hexagonal architecture.

Drawbacks: There’s still a struggle to execute. Even with the correct puzzle pieces, you might struggle to use them correctly. This is because the pattern-first developer still thinks predominantly in patterns. When faced with a problem, if the pattern doesn't exist, or you can't find it, you're stuck. Without a deeper level of the patterns (and why they’re used in the first place), it still feels like you’re just following best practice. Only, this time, it’s the DDD-best practices. The dominant unconscious conflict is "am I doing this right?" “is this the right DDD-way to do this?”

⚡️ To Mastery! The 4 Pillars: At this phase, you excel at the main DDD techniques BUT you struggle with strategy, testing, and core design/arch confidence under unique circumstances.

What we’ll do to improve in the course: Learn the how to uncover the domain & implement various frontend and backend patterns, enabling you to decouple from infrastructure, encapsulate complexity & introduce powerful testing strategies on any side of the stack.

Key topics: Domain-Driven Design, Hexagonal Architecture, Testing Strategies

Responsibility-First

Paradigm: The key paradigm shift in the Responsibility-First phase is a refined understanding of patterns — to see the instead in terms of stereotypical roles, responsibilities & their collaborations.

Context: Upon realizing that you need to develop core design confidence, you learn a Design Method. The most foundational one being Responsibility-Driven Design. This takes you into Object-Oriented Design, teaches you that everything is exactly the same — frontend, backend, desktop, etc — and this gives you the foundation for low-level OO design AND high-level systems design. You understand how to glue systems together, with or without patterns. Your thinking — your problem decomposition processes — they’re extremely fine-tuned. With the deepest level of understanding, you’re feeling excited to explore and take on more ambitious challenges.

Drawbacks: Responsibility-first developers tend to be great at continuing to challenge themselves, but need to pay closer attention to over-engineering solutions and keeping code understandable to other developers. Sometimes it’s better to use infrastructural components rather than build things yourself. This is especially important for topics you need more experience in, which is most commonly Messaging.

⚡️ To Mastery! The 4 Pillars: At this phase, you can break problems down into the smallest atomic units (ie: responsibilities for doings & knowings), assemble responsibilities into roles, and design collaborations using stereotypical solutions. Basically, you’re a pattern-matching, categorizing, clarification-machine. Theoretically, you understand what to do and why it’ll work. But you still need experiences. You have a high level of design, architecture, testing & strategy confidence for challenges you’ve personally explored. Uncertainty still lies in unexplored topics, techniques and tools, but you have the confidence to know you can figure them out quickly, understanding their purpose and how they play together with the larger picture of the Stereotypical Architecture and the 12 Essentials.

What we’ll do to improve in the course: Learn how to balance coupling & cohesion, architect & design anything using RDD, the Stereotypical Architecture & the timeless 3-Step Responsibility-Driven Design process.

Key topics: Responsibility-Driven Design, The Stereotypical Architecture, Messaging

Value-First

Paradigm: The final paradigm is the paradigm is the most strategic one; Value-First developers prioritize optimizing the Value of everything they do, looking for the clearest path towards the most beneficial outcomes, even if it means not writing any code.

Context: Having gotten to the deepest level of abstraction (ie: Responsibility-First), Value-First developers take the essential principle of Abstraction to the extreme. Sometimes called Software Craftsmen (ie: Sandro Mancuso), at first glance, Value-First developers appear to be unpredictable. Sometimes they don’t write any tests, sometimes they completely cover a feature in 4 different types of tests. Sometimes they write quick, crappy code and sometimes they write exceptional enterprise code. Whether they’re solopreneurs, staff developers, or lone developers holding the weight of the world at an early stage startup, Value-First developers are fluid and take action conducive to the environment they work.

Drawbacks: Hardly a drawback, Value-First developers tend to face a more existential challenge — knowing what you want in your career, which types of problems you’d like to solve in the world, and having the confidence to take the first steps in a new direction.

⚡️ To Mastery! The 4 Pillars: At this phase, you make decisions based on Value. You work strategically, using design methods and strategic thinking to make decisions. You know how to design extendable, valuable architectures on any layer of the stack, on frontend, backend, etc AND can strategize, test, design & arch confidently. With an understanding of the first principles, you're no longer bogged down by programming tasks. That's breathing to you. What's more important are your decisions. How are you Giving-Back-Time or Enriching-Time?

What we’ll do to improve in the course: Learn how to use the Systems Thinking-based FA²STR design method to systematically decompose any design problem in a consistent way.

Key topics: Systems Thinking, The Guess Points, The Ideal Developer Workflow, FA²STR

In summary

Each Phase of Craftship marks a new paradigm of thinking — how you’ll use abstraction to decompose problems. As you progress to the later stages, your thinking is deeper, more refined, and closer to the First Principles of this domain of software development. From later stages, you’ll have more confidence to make decisions that lead to beneficial outcomes.

  2. Learn what we’re going to build & how we’re going to use assignments, exercises & assessments to help you progress up the Phases of Craftship
